{{primary sources|date=November 2012}}
The '''Video Standards Council''' (VSC) is an administrator of the [[Pan European Game Information|PEGI]] system of [[Video game rating|age rating for video games]]. It was established in 1989, and has been responsible for the age ratings of [[video game]]s sold in the UK since 2012.<ref name="BBCVSC">{{cite news|title=Video Standards Council to take over games age ratings|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-18017385|publisher=BBC News|date=10 May 2012|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> The organisation is accountable to the [[Department of Culture, Media and Sport]].
==History== The VSC was established in 1989 following concerns from the [[Home Secretary]] about the video industry.<ref>{{cite web|title=VSC - ParentPort|url=http://www.parentport.org.uk/find-out-more/VSC|website=www.parentport.org.uk|accessdate=17 April 2017}}</ref> The organisation designed a [[Code of practice|code of practise]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Origins of the VSC|url=http://www.videostandards.org.uk/VSC/origins.html|publisher=The Video Standards Council|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> to ensure that the video and [[video game industry|video games industries]] delivered their products to the public responsibly. It also provides [[retailer]]s with staff training courses concerning the supply of age restricted videos, DVDs, and video games.
Since 1994, the VSC has been responsible for the age ratings of video games. Initially, they worked on behalf of the [[UK Interactive Entertainment Association]] (formerly ELSPA). Since 2003, they have been administrators of the [[Pan European Game Information|PEGI system]], which was incorporated into [[Law of the United Kingdom|UK law]] in 2012. Since then, the VSC has been the [[statutory body]] responsible for the age rating of video games in the UK,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Video Standards Council|url=http://videostandards.org.uk/VSC/|website=videostandards.org.uk|accessdate=17 April 2017|language=en}}</ref> which it does through its sub-body, the Games Rating Authority (GRA). The GRA also rates games for at least 30 other European countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Games Rating Authority|url=http://www.videostandards.org.uk/GRA/|publisher=The Video Standards Council|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Isn't the GRA a new company?|url=http://www.gamesratingauthority.org/pegi/gra.html|publisher=Games Rating Authority|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Video Standards Council Releases Annual Report on UK Video Games Ratings|url=http://gamepolitics.com/2013/07/23/video-standards-council-releases-annual-report-uk-video-games-ratings#.Uu45UHm2v4I|publisher=Game Politics|date=23 July 2013|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>
